Aims and Purpose
The overarching purpose of this project is to learn critical and interpretive cultural heritage
material (CHM) digitization for preservation and access. This entails a series of choices for project
management and execution of CHM digitization and machine/human-access. Within this the purpose I
analyzed the materials and the steps of the process itself, and learned to make informed critical,
interpretive, technological, and descriptive choices that I felt suited the subject matter, project purpose,
intended audience, and available resources.
The cultural heritage aim of the project is to digitally preserve and present the photo albums of
Signe Elvira Elgh b. 1900 in Molkom, Sweden; to provide the communities of Molkom, Loka, Grythyttan,
and Kristinehamn with an archival photo and descriptive record of its inhabitants from the early 1900s;
to preserve the visual and social histories of these communities; and to do so in a way that
demonstrates critical, interpretive, and reparative digitization best practices. Reparative description is a
term coined by Lael Hughes-Watkins in 2018 to name the role of revising archival metadata in social
justice (Olson, 2023). I expand that notion here to include all the interpretive choices made during
digitization, with best practices that ideally remediate harm, sidelining, and erasure of marginalized
communities while restoring history and regenerating archival equity. In this project, I have attempted
to do this by creating gender-coding and status sensitive metadata (controlled vocabularies, natural
language descriptions, and Viras early analog social tagging of her classmates), as well as naming the
non-male gaze of the featured photography studios of the 1910s.
The project goals are to digitally preserve ageing cultural heritage material (an album of
photographs) through photography and digital scanning; to create gender-coding-, and status-sensitive
descriptive metadata for the photographs; to display these photographs and their descriptive metadata
on the web and therefore findable and accessible to machines and humans; and to present the digital

Reparative Metadata
What is reparative metadata?
The 2022 paper Decolonizing your library: metadata that empowers, by Kelley Rowan and Annia
Gonzalez accessibly summarizes their reparative metadata project as metadata remediation plan that
ameliorates the harm done by antiquated language. Recognizing the need to work in a liminal space
between neutrality and partiality (Carbajal, 2021) that in turn gives space to recognize harmful
language, Rowan and Gonzalez give an example of regularly encountered descriptions such as 450,000
illegal aliens live and work in the city of Miami then employ enough partiality to recognize the harmful
language choices and still retain enough neutrality to replace the language with something more
inclusive; 450,000 non-citizens live and work in the city of Miami
The first step Rowan and Gonzalez took was creating a thesaurus to recognize and replace
harmful language under the following categories: ableist, ageist, history and society, homophobic,
laudatory, racist, sexist, and religious discrimination. Then, working beyond identifying harmful
descriptive terms, remediating exclusive laudatory language which describes one person in glowing
terms and another person (usually marginalized) without such terms; and erasure which manifests as
something as simple as failing to name an individual in a photograph, failing to describe their existence
in a photo, or giving them a name that reflects their male counterpart rather than them. Other
measures are describing documents in the language of their creator. Rowan and Gonzalez call for next
steps such as bringing the community in to help describe the documents.

Tulane University Library with (unfortunately United-States-centric but easily accessible) A

Background
On the author/creator
Signe Elvira Vira Elgh was born in 1900 into a family that managed Loka Brunn from the early
1900s into the 1950s. She attended Kristinehamns Praktiskaskola from 1914 to 1917. After school, Vira
worked at Loka Brunn, Vira became a domestic worker in the house of a celebrated sculptor, and later
became a hairdresser, running her own hair salon. Ever the forward-thinking woman she had a child at
an older age and raised him alone, self-archiving for posterity because she knew her life and experiences
mattered. She kept photo memories of her life experiences and loved ones, and recorded an oral
herstory before her death hoping that it would share her life and times with her two grandchildren.
Because of her efforts, her great-grandchildren and their generation will experience the benefit of her
memory work.
On the photo album
Vira had several photo albums and a collection of photos. This particular album is one of her
schoolmates (and occasional friend and relative) from Kristinehamns Praktiska-skola from 1917-1918.

The album is a 20.3 cm x 25.4 cm x 7 cm case bound with front and back boards are dark blue velvet

The pages are paperboard window pockets with cloth attached to bind the signatures in the spine. The
pages are embossed round-topped window pockets. The paperboard is yellowed and mottled with age.
On acquiring the album
This album was given to Per Ingemar Elgh upon his mother Elviras death in 1988. Per Elgh kept
the album until his death in 2014. It was then passed to his son Per Mathias Elgh, then loaned to Per
Elghs then-daughter-in-law Nicole Elgh (project principal) in 2015. Nicole initially requested the albums
while searching for photos to create Pers funeral program.
On the photos
A number of the photos are graduation photos, but it is not known if they are Gymnasium
graduation photos or praktiska-skola graduation photos. Furthermore, only some of the photos are
inscribed with identifying information. A few photos were inscribed on the back and were removed for
further examination with care and concern that removing the photos may damage the fragile album
interior.
Some of the photo studios c. 1900-1920 are represented here: Atelier Rosn (Linkping),
Systrarna Hallberg (Kristinehamn), Johanna Lundbck (Grythyttehed and Loka), K.G. Wiborgh
(Kristinehamn), and Sw. Swensson (Sven Svensson) Kungliga Hoffotografaren (Linkping) (Johanson,
n.d.).

Earlier Similar Projects and Relevance
Earlier similar projects in Swedish preserving cultural heritage for Vrmland, Kristinehamn,
Grythyttan, Grythyttehed, and Loka are part of DigitaltMuseum (https://digitaltmuseum.se/) with their
digitized memory albums, many individual local history pages, and the community portrait sharing on
Rtter.se (a Swedish genealogy site with photos). However, I am not aware at this time of a Swedish
project that focuses on remediating gender-based harm in digitized photo metadata, particularly in
personal photo albums or school photos.
For reasons explained later in this paper, this project has relevance to the reparative description
community and the critical photo metadata community (projects such as Homosaurus, Trans Metadata
Collective, MyPronouns.org, Mrs. His Name Project) and for its representation-is-not-gender approach
to photo description; to the feminist community for representation of a single mother self-archiving
(Svenskt kvinnobiografiskt lexikon devoted to increased visibility of women's lives, as well as the early
push for women self-archiving led by the Lesbian Herstory Archives); to the local Swedish community
and historical societies (Riksarkivet, DigitaltMuseum, Loka Brunn, Kristinehamn, Vrmland); to
genealogists and family historians (Rtter.se); to the Swedish photography history community
(Fotoregistret), particularly documenting the work of woman-owned and run photo studios in the early
1900s at a time when the scope of what was considered women's work, was very limited.

Legal Aspects & Copyright Status
This was carefully considered as the material was digitized and published in the United States,
but the author, subjects, and original documents are from Sweden and will be returned to Sweden.
Sweden adheres to the EUs copyright laws which are different; while the United States has death of
the creator plus 70 years for works created after 1923 (Hirtle, et. Al, 2009). This may pertain to the
photo studio/photographer; those depicted in the photos and their families; the creator of the photo
album and her inscriptions. Digitization and digital facsimiles are the intellectual property rights of the
person who digitized the image, and their permission must be obtained. In my case, I give permission for
Fair Use only; all other uses must be cleared with me.
Ethical Data
The most sensitive information resource in the original collection that was acquired was the
audio recordings of Elviras life history on cassette tape. These recordings may contain sensitive
information about family and social relationships, sensitive information about events, actions and
behaviors involving people who were not present in or consenting to the recording, information about
property, finances, or other types of information deemed sensitive. Likewise, it is possible that some of
these photographs and the people depicted in them are private in nature. For example, a misgendered
young person may reserve the right to keep images of their misgendered presentation private. Since I
cannot know the wishes of the people depicted in the photos, I am instead taking a reparative metadata
approach and attempting to sensitively describe the contents of the photograph. Some descendants of
those pictured, however, may take offense at the reparative approach for example, if I do not describe
someone they consider grandmother as she/her or describe them as a woman. It is important to
state that in doing that, my gender-neutral description in no way implies one thing or the other about
the persons actual gender.

Metadata
To what kinds of metadata does reparative descriptive metadata apply?
Of the six kinds of metadata: structural, descriptive, preservation, administrative, provenance,
and definitional, this project primarily illustrates reparative practice within descriptive, administrative,
and provenance. It addresses remediation of harmful controlled vocabularies, natural language
description, and provenance omissions.
Embedded photo structural metadata was first added to the files by the scanner, to which I may
have added descriptive, administrative, provenance, and definitional metadata to the digital photo files
in GIMP. I then exported that embedded metadata to XML files to created access to machines and
people through XSLT transformation, displayable on the web.
On the metadata schemas and controlled vocabularies
Working with photographic metadata entailed considering embedded and descriptive schemes
this meant that I was going to work with Exif, IPTC (old standard), XMP (newer standard), and Dublin
Core fields. Paid photo editing software such as Adobe default to XMP, a robust and collaborate
metadata schema for digital image sidecar files that are a combination of XML and RDF, as a standard.
Although both IPTC and XMP metadata were easy to add and export into an XML file in GIMP, it
frustratingly exported my XML metadata files with unexpected non UTF-8 characters that required me
to go into each file and remove them before the XML was error-free.
Editing embedded metadata
As mentioned above GIMP was used to edit the embedded photo metadata. Available schemas
included GIMP Description, IPTC, XMP, and EXIF. I entered metadata into IPTC and XMP fields and
exported from GIMP to XML. The metadata was browsed using ExifTool. Interoperability between IPTC

Descriptive Language
Similar materials on DigitaltMuseum provided ideas for both controlled vocabularies and natural
language descriptions from the Swedish point of view. Name-authority, subject-authority, and form-
genre authority cues were taken from DigitaltMuseums descriptions. I merged this with reparative
metadata standards and strategies from the projects mentioned above. As a key feature of my project,
deciding how to describe the photos was a painstaking process and entailed research ranging from
gender to period clothing styles and military uniforms.

Materials to digitize
I had initially considered a number of projects, most of them involving traveling to digitize slave
ship logbooks or plantation records. Due to my life circumstances, unfortunately, those were not
feasible. One project I started, (one of several false starts) was of orphanage records which I promptly
stopped after realizing that that information couldnt be made public.
Elviras materials were already accessible. However, working with Elviras materials, I had
initially chosen media that was difficult (at the time) to make accessible to the public. Her school photo
album proved to be the right size, compact, with a pre-determined theme and order, with some
labeling. Digitizing a self-styled yearbook from the self-archiving efforts of an enterprising solo parent
who identified as a cis woman (for lack of other choices) in 1900s-1980's Sweden seem to be good

Sourcing and Legal Rights
As mentioned earlier, this material was sourced from my childs father, Mathias, after his own
father died. He sent it to the United States after I left Sweden so that I could digitize it, as another family
member was interested in seeing and possessing it. With Mathias family as the copyright holder, the
only issue was to understand if I could make images of the people represented in the photos, public.
According to U.S. law, I could, as most of them were born over 120 years ago, and the photos taken over
100 years ago.
Image Capture
A self-service book scanner at the University of Colorado, Boulder library was easily accessible.
The resolution was not on the level of those used for rare books and the highest-level preservation
efforts; nor did I have access to a quality camera and studio setup to photograph the book or pages
uniformly. So, the self-service KIC (Knowledge Imaging Center) BookEye scanner at the library seemed
the best option. Its cradle was very gentle on the book, it captured all of the information that I needed
(with the exception of a sharp image of the metal embellishment on the cover of the album which
consistently cause a bright reflection until I moved it to a distance which it would not capture the
sharpest image). I was able to create TIFF, PNG, and JPEG at resolutions up to 16 megapixels. The
positioning of the book, however, was limited to the book cradle, as was the color background. I could
have conceivably laid down a large sheet of colored paper in the cradle beneath the book, but I did not.
Information not captured
As I described in the previous section, I chose the cropping option, and information from the
pages edges and how they are situated in the book is missing. I also did not have the camera to

Digital file
Preservation file format
Conventional wisdom holds that TIFF is the file format of choice for archival digitization of
photographs (Terras, 2008). Therefore, most archival master image files will be in TIFF format. However,
my decision to save the master files as PNG was dictated both by PNGs near comparable quality and
smaller file sizeconstraints dictated by the resources I had available. Like TIFF, PNG is a lossless 16-
and 8-bit format (Terras, 2008). PNGs are nearly as good as TIFF when it comes to image quality,
especially for primarily digital use. TIFF is the standard when it comes to print media, but PNG works
quite well for digital graphics (Terras, 2008).
Presentation file format
At the book scanner, I saved one set of master files in PNG and one set of display files in JPEG.
These differing formats were produced from the original scans at the scanner at the time of scanning, I
did not convert PNG to JPEG later. I chose JPEG (.jpg) as a presentation format due to its image-quality-
for-size. I knew that I would be making a flipbook and uploading more portable versions of these images,
so JPEG seemed to be the natural choice for presentation.
Resolution
I made several mistakes while working with the KIC stations. I had hoped to capture 16-bit TIFF
images, however, due to space constraints around having to email the files directly from the KIC station I
settled for 8-bit PNGs. I planned to return to the book scanner with another storage strategy and scan

On the descriptive choices
The descriptive metadata was done with attention to reparative metadata practices described
below, this time with an emphasis on naming married women and recognizing gender range and so has
avoided omitting women's first and maiden names and avoided gendering those pictured as their self-
understood genders were not known. Guidelines advise not to assume information that isnt there or
included with the primary source (Tulane, 2024), and I think that inferring gender from name follows
this advice.
The descriptions were assisted by Jesse Pollak, a documentary photographer with a seasoned
eye for how photos are described. Her own gender fluidity and academic background documenting the
trans sex-work community in Mexico gives her a sensitivity toward gender presentation and designation
in photographs.
Software used
Image editing
Due to budget constraints, I used GIMP for image editing, although I did not have to do much
editing because the KIC stations have a function that allows for you to choose to crop the scans before
sending/downloading them. I should have chosen no cropping, however, because I feel that I lost some
spatial and material context with the cropping that I would have preferred to remain on original scans.
Encoding
Due to budget constraints, free software and online services were used. GIMP, GitHub, and
Notepad ++ were my primary software choices.

Preservation platform(s)
On the technical choices
Initially, I wasnt sure where I would be able to preserve these files in a way that provided long-
term access. After some research, I chose Omeka. However, I interpreted some aspects of the
assignment as calling for scripting and working with the metadata in XML format. Furthermore, I needed
a way to embed and share the embedded metadata in each digital image. So, I moved the project from
Omeka to GitHub. GitHub is a reliable and accessible repository that keeps records of every action
performed on image and text files, and was recommended by the instructors of this course, so it seemed
a safe and reliable choice.
Presentation platform(s)
Technical infrastructure
Initially, Omeka seemed a simple and long-term preservation-oriented solution but did not fulfill
the requirements of my assignment. GitHub pages seemed easy enough, especially with a template
already having been prepared by an instructor. However, the refresh time due to page caching on the
servers hampered my coding speed considerably. In the future, I would not develop on GitHub pages
but instead, develop pages offline in a local directory.
Presentation design
Like many others, I felt the flipbook format to be a nice simulation of browsing through this
photo album, especially for my audience who has not spent sufficient time on the web to tire of this sort
of thing. It is reminiscent of the analog era, and I thought it fitting for a 100+ year old memory album.
However, finding aesthetic (and free) flipbook solutions was difficult. I chose to feature a flipbook as an
engagement feature on the landing page, but not as the primary vehicle for viewing the photographs
and descriptions. I chose instead to hard-code the images on a separate HTML using GitHub pages.

Methodological Considerations
The initial selection journey
This project was a long and arduous decision-making process. It began in 2021 with the
acquisition of the photo books here in the US (sent from Sweden) as well as cassette tapes. Initially, my
aim was to make Elviras oral herstory available, but the DCHM course did not have an instructor
specializing in audio recordings and I was discouraged from doing this. I had originally digitized the tapes
in 2017 while in Sweden, using a tape player and audio cable into the desktop PC. The quality of the
digitization was not great. The tapes were also quite fragile. As a result, the digitization was very noisy
and the voice volume was very low, and I needed to process the digitized audio files through noise
reduction filters. Mathias and I then attempted to painstakingly translate what she was saying into
English but found it difficult. I then created a TEI transcription of a printed poem called Minnen av Loka
Brunn that I would then pair with an album of photos from Loka Brunn, and a few of the paraphrased

the 260 project hours were put into false starts and seeing what was and wasnt viable/feasible.
Document attributes
Elviras photo album lent itself to digitization on a book scanner. Even if a 110-year-old photo
album is less of a priority than films and negatives which degenerate faster (cite), this object could easily
be lost to time, poor storage/handling, and other forms of degradation. Informational content could be
adequately captured in digital form, and the physical formats and condition of the material did not
represent major impediments. No intermediates were involved. The project was just large enough to be
project-worthy and just small enough to handle as a solo; it is not complex in variety but diverse enough
to make critical comparisons.
Preservation considerations
The material was put at moderate risk in the digitization process but at less risk than repeated
casual browsing that it may normally encounter as a family heirloom in a private collection. Digital
surrogates will definitely reduce use of the originals offering them protection from handling and a
change for physical conservation. The digital reproduction is not only seen as a means to replace the
originals but as a means to create access to their contents.
Organization and available documentation
The material is a photo album with a clear theme and is in a coherent, logically structured order.
It is not paginated by number, but the arrangement suggested by placement by the original creator. Is it
complete insofar as some missing photographs were removed by the creator and are likely to be found

Intended uses
I anticipate these resources being used at the same frequency similar content on
DigitaltMuseum, or similar resources via Rtter, Riksarkivet pages; Vrmland's pages; Kristinehamns
Praktiska-skola Facebook and web pages; and Fotografregistret are accessed. This information might be
gathered from page view or download information from servers. My understanding of user
requirements is that they will want educational, private, journalistic, or civic use of the original digitized
files as well as a place to browse the collection and its metadata, and digitization can support these
uses. This collections existence wasnt initially known outside of Elviras descendants. However, a
relative who is a family historian has recently requested the photographs. This will resolve the limited
access that all family members have to the physical primary source. Thus, on both counts the
collection coming to be released and the ability for all family to access its contents as well as material
conservation will be significantly enhanced by digitization. The files and GitHub repository on which they
are situated can support a range of uses such as printing, browsing, and detailed review. There are no
issues that I know of around security or access to the digital files that I can think of. However, access to
the original documents would certainly have been restricted due to their fragility and private
possession.

Duplication of effort
This material has not already been digitized by another trusted source. Only the digital files that
I have produced and will continue to produce possess sufficient quality, documentation, and
functionality to serve my purposes, unless after publication, other sources come forth with negatives,
inscribed photos, and more contextual information about the album's depictions and contents. Fair Use
(U.S. Copyright Act) conditions govern access and use of the files that I have produced; use conditions
for any duplicate digitization files that I have not yet encountered are unknown.

Finances
I can determine the total cost of image acquisition (selection, preparation, capture, indexing,
and quality control) if I am to 1) estimate my fee for the time; 2) record the ideal technical equipment
and software costs. However, no institutional budget was established for this project and the costs
needed to be kept to a minimum. This majorly impacted the technological choices that were made, and
the labor hours were student-intern labor hours resulting in class credit rather than money paid. Thus,
the cost is justified for the real and perceived benefits that will accrue from digitization. In a scenario
where labor wages are factored in and the optimal equipment and software are used, I would say that
more justification would have to be established by consulting communities, historical societies,
institutions, consortia, and the like. 260 hours at the average archivist rate of $27.46/hr (BLS.gov, 2024)
is a significant amount of money. Adding in server costs, software costs, equipment rental or acquisition,
and conservation supplies, I would recommend this project as part of a larger initiative for the purposes
of offsetting the costs or at least for it to be performed more efficiently in terms of time. The is currently
no external institutional commitment, only individual archivist commitment to the ongoing
management and preservation of these files on GitHub which has protocols for archiving, preservation,
and migration.
Critical Analysis of Methodology
Most of this report has detailed a process born of critical departures from standard
methodology. I limited the scope of my decisions based on limited resources available to me, rather
than solely on a subjective interpretive basis (Davis-Kronlund, personal communication January 2019).
Rather than solely depending on Library of Congress controlled vocabulary thesauri, I acknowledged not

only my non-Swedish positionality and used DigitaltMuseum controlled vocabulary and natural language
descriptions of similar material as guides. Departing from problematic Library of Congress descriptive
practices, I leaned into my bias for reparative, gender-expansive metadata for social justice (Hughes-
Watkins, 2018; Carbajal, 2022). Departing from standards of using TIFF for master files (Terras, 2008) I
instead chose to use using PNG for master files in an extensible version of the More Product, Less
Process approach (Santamaria, 2015) approach to digital heritage archiving with limited resources.
Limitations and Future Directions
Limitations
Resources
Limitations of this project were primarily financial and housing/storage instability constraints
that caused this project to be stopped and started again leading to lack of complete imaging
(photography, 16-bit digitization) and more developed metadata.
Positionality
For this course I have been trained through Swedish, German, and U.S.-sources, and have
applied that information to Swedish cultural heritage material, in United States English. Additionally, I
am primarily familiar with the United States reparative metadata canon including Archives For Black
Lives in Philadelphias anti-racist description resources (2022), Lael Hughes-Watkins' Moving toward a
reparative archive (2018), Ashley Vavras Right to be Forgotten (2014), Tonia Sutherlands Archival
Amnesty (2017), and Jessica Tais Cultural Humility (2021) to name a few. I am not well-versed in
Swedish projects to remediate and repair metadata in a similar way, and I dont doubt that they would
be most appropriate for this project. Suffice it to say that I am doing this work with a dual-citizen gaze
and a U.S.-centric method.

Future Directions
Future directions of this project include a complete photographing of the album and binding
with scale reference; re-scanning in TIFF format without edge cropping; ongoing conservation and
preservation of the original object/document in a protected light and climate-controlled storage
environment; handling protocol; maintenance of digital files in formats and on media that favor
perpetuity; migration of digital files and formats as needed for preservation; and maintenance of public
access channels to this digital repository along with the continual improvement of accompanying
metadata (culturally appropriate metadata, entering preservation metadata, provenance metadata,
etc.). A public digital archive of Elviras oral history recordings and transcriptions are my next step.
Lastly, I have planned to resume work on the Signe Elvira Elgh site on Omeka, as this helps me call for
community reparative metadata contribution (folksonomy), while adding a desired redundancy,
standardized indexing, and interoperability.
